Well, addiction is hard. It took me a year and a half of trying to "quit" marijuana, and I still don't really consider myself to have "quit", I just say "I'm abstaining, and have been abstaining for six months so far." I don't buy into the AA religious stuff, but I do think they're right about the idea that you don't stop being an alcoholic, you're just an alcoholic who isn't drinking. Alcohol has never been my vice, but I think that idea applies to every addiction. It's a fundamental part of me that I'm vulnerable to marijuana and porn addiction, and it will probably always be true. Marijuana is much easier to quit because I can distance myself from it, I only have to exert my willpower briefly to not buy anything, or to reject a joint if my friends are smoking, etc. For porn, it's much harder. I can't distance myself from it, there's no technological means I could use to stop my access to it that I couldn't subvert in minutes, and, perhaps worst of all, it doesn't as obviously impact my life. With marijuana, I was very motivated to quit because I wanted to get back to feeling sharp, never having to pass up an opportunity or event because I was stoned when it happened. Porn doesn't interfere with my life in as immediate of ways. It's a subtle thing, only in retrospect do I see how it sapped my motivation to pursue relationships and sexual relationships.

I have a lot of sympathy for those who struggle with addictions worse than mine, and I think we overlook how much our circumstances enable us to function with our vices, to ignore them without our life falling apart. "There but for the grace of God go I" - I think I'm the same as any addict, just lucky that my circumstances pushed me to things which didn't destroy my life, that my skills allowed me to not be financially impacted by wasting thousands on weed, that I had a family and friends already so that even if porn saps my motivation, I still had fulfilling relationships.
